-- this and super keywords

this: A reference to the instance variable or current object instance
super: A reference to the parent(base) object instance.

wht it is used?
Ambiguity: It tells JVM exactly which variable you have to access , which not

Efficiency: It allows Constructor Chaining, wwe can reuse initialization logic
instead of writing multiple times.

Usage in Website/Enterprise Applications
super: You might have a base Notification class. Whether it is an EmailNotification or a PushNotification,
both need to call super() to set the timeStamp and UserId defined in the parent

this: In a ProfileUpdate form, you use this.name = name to make sure name entering
in the web form is saved to the specific user's record in the database.

if parent has no-argument constructor, super() is used by default.
if the parent only has constructors with parameters, you must call it manually.
